(window.webpackJsonp=window.webpackJsonp||[]).push([[18],{284:function(e,t,o){"use strict";o.r(t);var s=o(13),a=Object(s.a)({},(function(){var e=this,t=e._self._c;return t("ContentSlotsDistributor",{attrs:{"slot-key":e.$parent.slotKey}},[t("h1",{attrs:{id:"lesson-8"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#lesson-8"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" LESSON 8")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"the-stoics-on-decision-making"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#the-stoics-on-decision-making"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" THE STOICS ON DECISION-MAKING")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The third and last of Epictetus’s disciplines is the discipline of assent, which is concerned with improving our ability to arrive at correct judgments so that we always act in the best way possible. In a  sense, the discipline of assent is a refinement of the other two, as it makes it easier and smoother to practice desire and aversion as well as action.")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"implementation-intention-exercise"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#implementation-intention-exercise"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" IMPLEMENTATION INTENTION EXERCISE")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The first exercise is based on Marcus Aurelius’s four examples of mental weakness: needless fancy, being antisocial, not speaking from the heart, and refusing to forgive yourself.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("How many times have you fallen for one or more of these moods of the mind only to regret it later on? For this exercise, pick one of the four moods to focus on.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("Let’s say that speaking from the heart is difficult for you, as you tend to want to please people. At the beginning of the first day, write a note to yourself saying that you intend to do a certain thing—what in modern psychological therapy is called an implementation intention.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("For instance, your implementation intention might read something like: “Whenever I feel the impulse to please people, I will not act immediately on it.”")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("It might also be useful to keep track of how many times a week you feel the need to please people and how many times you were able to counter the impulse. It’s OK to slip up once in a while. But with time, you should notice that the problematic behavior becomes less frequent.")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"precepts-exercise"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#precepts-exercise"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" PRECEPTS EXERCISE")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("In his 71st letter to his friend Lucilius, Seneca makes an analogy between the precepts of Stoicism and a wool cloth that gradually and thoroughly absorbs its color from being soaked in dye. Just like it takes time to properly color a garment, so it takes time to color one’s soul.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("We can imbue our souls with Stoic philosophy by keeping a number of short phrases ready at hand as constant and easy reminders of what we should do as Stoic practitioners. Every practitioner has their own list of favorite precepts, but here are five choices to get you started.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("Virtue is the only true good.")]),e._v(" When we say that virtue is the only true good, we mean that for a Stoic, the overarching aim is to act pro-socially, with the good of the human cosmopolis in mind. This precept reminds us that we should use everything else—money, property, and so on—in the service of the common good, not for selfish ends.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("Some things are up to me; others are not up to me.")]),e._v(" This is often referred to as the dichotomy of control. Only our judgments, considered opinions, and endorsed values are truly up to us. We might be able to influence outcomes, but ultimately, they are determined by factors outside of our control. That’s why reciting this Stoic precept before a job interview or a first date will remind us that we should focus on maximizing our efforts and accept whatever comes with equanimity.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("Nothing lasts forever.")]),e._v(" Reminding ourselves that nothing lasts forever can be helpful in countless circumstances. For instance, you’re having a long day at work. The good news is that it won’t last forever! Another thing that won’t last forever, of course, is your physical being. Since you don’t know how much time you have left, why not skip the stuff that’s unimportant and focus on what you want to get done in life?")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("Everything changes.")]),e._v(" This Greek aphorism predates the Stoics, going back to the philosopher Heraclitus, whose metaphysics strongly influenced the Stoic view of the world. Even things that might seem not to change—like mountains and continents—evolve over time, though at such a slow pace that the change might be imperceptible to the human eye. Change is normal, so it’s senseless to resist it. Kids grow up, friends move to other places, jobs are lost and found, and we grow older.\n57\nLesson 8 The Stoics on Decision-Making")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("I will do it, fate permitting.")]),e._v(" To a Stoic, the word fate doesn’t have to be interpreted in terms of the existence of a grand plan laid out for the whole universe. It might simply mean that we have the intention of doing a given thing, but we’re also aware that something outside of our control could get in the way. For example, you will deliver that report to your boss at the end of the month—unless something serious prevents you from completing it. The point is not to give ourselves excuses to back away from our commitments but rather to be realistic that while our intentions are up to us, the outcomes of our actions are not entirely\nat our command.")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"temperance-exercise"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#temperance-exercise"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" TEMPERANCE EXERCISE")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The next exercise is inspired by a passage in Marcus Aurelius’s Meditations in which he reminds himself that he likes certain pleasures of the flesh—exotic food, wine, and sex—too much, and that it’s wiser for him to practice temperance.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("This exercise is meant to help us bring strong urges under control by redescribing the objects of our desires in a more detached fashion—stripping them of the value judgments that we automatically imposed but that are not in fact part of them.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("For instance, if you are too fond of wine, remind yourself that what you prize is just fermented grape juice. The point is not to take away but rather to moderate such desires and prevent you from feeling too virtuous when, in fact, you aren’t.")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"anger-exercise"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#anger-exercise"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" ANGER EXERCISE")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The next exercise, inspired by Seneca’s book On Anger, concerns one of the major issues that worried the Stoics: outbursts of anger. Seneca considered these fits of emotion to be a kind of temporary madness.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("He tells us not to try to control anger, which is next to impossible, but rather to disengage from the situation so that our anger subsides on its own. Then, and only then, will we be in a position to reengage rationally and see what needs to be done.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("Disengagement for the purpose of gaining some cognitive distance between you and your anger can be done in a number of ways. They’re simple but effective techniques, including taking a walk, retiring to another room for a few minutes, counting to 20, reciting the alphabet, or engaging in a few deep breaths. Once we’ve recovered our composure, we can engage in calm analytical thinking.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("When we recognize the initial symptoms of anger, we have a small window of opportunity to disengage before the anger develops and pushes reason aside. Once we’ve regained our composure, we can engage in an exercise of cognitive self-challenge by trying to convince our more emotional self that there really is nothing to get angry about.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("To carry out this exercise, reflect on an episode of anger that you’ve experienced\nrecently. Write down the specifics. For instance, create a table with two columns:\none labeled “object of anger” and the other labeled “possible rebuttals.” Then populate the table with your specific example. The goal is to move toward preventing a similar occurrence in the future by preparing yourself to deal with the source of anger.")]),e._v(" "),t("blockquote",[t("p",[e._v("Studies show the best boxers are those who keep their cool in the ring. Those who get angry start throwing ineffective punches, driven by their rage instead of their brains, and they tend to lose the fight.")])]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"judgment-exercise"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#judgment-exercise"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" JUDGMENT EXERCISE")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The last exercise for the discipline of assent comes from Epictetus’s Enchiridion. He states:")]),e._v(" "),t("ul",[t("li",[e._v("If a man wash quickly, do not say that he washes badly, but that he washes quickly. If a man drink much wine, do not say that he drinks badly, but that he drinks much. For until you have decided what judgment prompts him, how do you\nknow that he acts badly?")])]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The idea is that we should be careful in judging others. Often, we simply don’t know enough about other people and their motivations to arrive at a sound judgment of what they’re doing. And other people’s actions are up to them—not us—and we should focus on improving our own judgments.")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The way to practice this is as follows: For a full day, or a full week, every time you catch yourself judging someone, stop and rephrase the situation in more neutral terms. For instance, suppose you’re a food snob. Instead of saying, “I can’t believe that guy is putting Parmesan cheese on pasta with seafood,” say, “that guy is combining culinary ingredients in a way different from what most Italians would.”")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("The point is that the world would be significantly better if we followed the Stoic advice of being less judgmental of others and more focused on improving ourselves.")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"suggested-readings"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#suggested-readings"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" SUGGESTED READINGS")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("Pigliucci and Lopez, A Handbook for New Stoics.")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"question"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#question"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" QUESTION")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("What is the discipline of assent?")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("Answer on page 181")]),e._v(" "),t("h1",{attrs:{id:"第-8-课"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#第-8-课"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 第 8 课")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"斯多葛主义的决策论"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#斯多葛主义的决策论"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 斯多葛主义的决策论")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("爱比克泰德的第三个也是最后一个原则是"),t("strong",[e._v("同意的纪律")]),e._v("（discipline of assent）（Stoic Mindfulness），它与提高我们做出正确判断的能力有关，以便我们始终以最好的方式行动。从某种意义上说，"),t("strong",[e._v("同意的纪律")]),e._v("是对其他两个纪律的改进，因为它使练习欲望和厌恶以及行动变得更容易和更顺畅。")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"执行意图练习"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#执行意图练习"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 执行意图练习")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("第一个练习是基于 Marcus Aurelius 的四个心理弱点的例子：不必要的幻想、反社会、不发自内心地说话和拒绝原谅自己。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("有多少次，你沉迷于其中一种或多种情绪，但后来又后悔了？对于这个练习，选择四种情绪中的一种来关注。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("假设发自内心地说话对你来说很困难，因为你倾向于取悦别人。在第一天开始的时候，给自己写一张便条，说你打算做某件事——这在现代心理治疗中被称为执行意图（ implementation intention）。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("例如，你的执行意图可能是这样的：“每当我有取悦他人的冲动时，我不会立即采取行动。”")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("记录下一周有多少次你觉得需要取悦别人，又有多少次你能够抑制这种冲动，这可能也是有用的。偶尔出点差错没什么大不了的。但随着时间的推移，你应该注意到问题行为变得越来越少。")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"戒律练习"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#戒律练习"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 戒律练习")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("在他给朋友卢西利厄斯的第 71 封信中，塞内卡将斯多葛主义的戒律与羊毛布进行了类比，羊毛布会逐渐彻底地吸收其颜色，使其浸入染料中。就像给衣服上色需要时间一样，给一个人的灵魂上色也需要时间。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("我们可以通过随时准备一些简短的短语来为我们的灵魂灌输斯多葛哲学，作为斯多葛学派实践者我们应该做的持续而简单的提醒。每个练习者都有自己最喜欢的戒律列表，但这里有五个选择可以帮助您入门。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("美德是唯一真正的善。")]),e._v(" 当我们说美德是唯一真正的善时，我们的意思是，对于斯多葛派来说，首要目标是采取亲社会行动，同时考虑到人类世界的利益。这个戒律提醒我们，我们应该使用其他一切——金钱、财产等等——为公共利益服务，而不是为了自私的目的。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("有些事情由我决定；其他的我不能决定。")]),e._v(" 这通常被称为控制的二分法。只有我们的判断、深思熟虑的意见和认可的价值观才真正取决于我们。我们也许能够影响结果，但最终，它们是由我们无法控制的因素决定的。这就是为什么在面试或第一次约会之前背诵这条斯多葛主义的戒律会提醒我们，我们应该专注于最大限度地努力，并接受任何伴随而来的平静。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("没有什么是永恒不变的。")]),e._v(" 提醒自己没有什么是永恒的，这在无数情况下都会有所帮助。例如，您在工作中度过了漫长的一天。好消息是它不会永远持续下去！当然，另一件事不会永远持续下去，那就是你的身体。既然你不知道自己还剩下多少时间，为什么不跳过不重要的事情，专注于你想要在生活中完成的事情呢？")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("一切都在改变。")]),e._v(" 这句希腊格言早于斯多葛派，可以追溯到哲学家赫拉克利特，他的形而上学强烈影响了斯多葛派的世界观。即使是看起来不会改变的事物——比如山脉和大陆——也会随着时间的推移而发展，尽管速度如此缓慢，以至于人眼可能察觉不到这种变化。变化是正常的，抗拒它是没有意义的。孩子们长大了，朋友们搬到了其他地方，工作丢失了又找到了，我们也变老了。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[t("strong",[e._v("如果命运允许，我会这样做。")]),e._v(" 对于斯多葛派来说，命运这个词不必解释为存在为整个宇宙制定的宏伟计划。这可能只是意味着我们有做某件事的意图，但我们也意识到我们无法控制的事情可能会妨碍我们。例如，您将在月底将该报告提交给您的老板——除非有严重的事情阻止您完成它。关键不是给自己找借口来背弃我们的承诺，而是要现实一点，虽然我们的意图取决于我们自己，但我们行动的结果并不完全在我们的掌握之中。")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"禁酒练习"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#禁酒练习"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 禁酒练习")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("下一个练习的灵感来自 Marcus Aurelius 的《沉思录》中的一段话，他在其中提醒自己，他太喜欢肉体的某些乐趣——异国情调的食物、葡萄酒和性——太多了，他认为练习节制是更明智的做法。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("这个练习旨在帮助我们控制强烈的冲动，通过以一种更超脱的方式重新描述我们的欲望对象——把我们自动强加给它们的、但实际上不是它们一部分的价值判断剥离出来。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("例如，如果您太喜欢葡萄酒，请提醒自己，您所珍视的只是发酵的葡萄汁。关键不是要消除这种欲望，而是要节制这种欲望，防止你觉得自己太善良，而实际上你并不是。")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"愤怒练习"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#愤怒练习"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 愤怒练习")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("下一个练习受到 Seneca 的《论愤怒》一书的启发，涉及斯多葛派担心的主要问题之一：愤怒的爆发。塞内卡认为这些情绪的发作是一种暂时的疯狂。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("他告诉我们不要试图控制愤怒，这几乎是不可能的，而是要脱离这种情况，这样我们的愤怒就会自行消退。然后，也只有到那时，我们才能重新理性地参与进来，看看需要做些什么。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("为了在你和你的愤怒之间获得一些认知距离而脱离接触可以通过多种方式完成。它们是简单但有效的技巧，包括散步、退到另一个房间几分钟、数到 20、背诵字母表或进行几次深呼吸。一旦我们恢复了冷静，我们就可以进行冷静的分析思考。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("当我们认识到愤怒的最初症状时，我们有一小段机会在愤怒发展并将理性推到一边之前脱离接触。一旦我们恢复了镇静，我们就可以进行认知自我挑战，试图说服情绪化的自己，真的没有什么可生气的。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("要进行此练习，请反思您最近经历过的愤怒事件。写下具体情况。例如，创建一个包含两列的表：\n一个标记为“愤怒的对象”，另一个标记为“可能的反驳”。然后用您的具体示例填充表格。目标是通过让自己准备好应对愤怒的根源，从而防止将来发生类似的事情。")]),e._v(" "),t("blockquote",[t("p",[e._v("研究表明，最好的拳击手是那些在拳击场上保持冷静的人。那些生气的人开始挥出无效的拳头，由他们的愤怒而不是他们的大脑驱动，他们往往会输掉这场战斗。")])]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"判断练习"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#判断练习"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 判断练习")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("同意的纪律（discipline of assent）的最后一个练习来自 Epictetus 的 《Enchiridion》。他说：")]),e._v(" "),t("ul",[t("li",[e._v("如果一个人洗得快，不要说他洗得不好，而是说他洗得快。如果一个人喝了很多酒，不要说他喝得不好，而是说他喝多了。因为你若不知道他的判断是什么，你怎么知道他的行为是坏的呢?")])]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("这个想法是，我们应该谨慎地评价别人。通常，我们对他人以及他们的动机了解不够，无法对他们的行为做出合理的判断。其他人的行为是由他们自己决定的，而不是我们自己，我们应该专注于改善我们自己的判断。")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("练习方法如下：一整天或一整周，每当你发现自己在评判某人时，停下来，用更中性的措辞重新表述情况。例如，假设你是一个对食物很挑剔的人。与其说“我不敢相信那个人把帕尔马干酪和海鲜放在意大利面上”，不如说，“那个人正在以一种与大多数意大利人不同的方式结合烹饪原料。”")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("关键是，如果我们遵循斯多葛派的建议，减少对他人的评判，更专注于改善自己，世界将会变得更好。")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"推荐读物"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#推荐读物"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 推荐读物")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("Pigliucci 和 Lopez，新斯多葛学派手册。")]),e._v(" "),t("h2",{attrs:{id:"问题"}},[t("a",{staticClass:"header-anchor",attrs:{href:"#问题"}},[e._v("#")]),e._v(" 问题")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("同意的纪律是什么？")]),e._v(" "),t("p",[e._v("第 181 页的答案")])])}),[],!1,null,null,null);t.default=a.exports}}]);